  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This article presents an updated catalogue of split-GAL4 driver lines specifically targeting descending neurons in the model organism Drosophila melanogaster. The work showcases valuable contributions from prominent institutions, including the Howard Hughes Medical Institute and the University of Cambridge, highlighting its solid academic foundation.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The updated catalogue of split-GAL4 driver lines for descending neurons in Drosophila melanogaster, published in eLife, represents a significant contribution to our understanding of neuronal circuits in this widely used model organism. The collaborative effort includes distinguished institutions such as the Howard Hughes Medical Institute, West Virginia University, Leipzig University, and the University of Cambridge, emphasizing a broad institutional support behind the research.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">While specific metrics related to citations, online mentions, and social discourse are currently absent, the meticulous curation of this catalogue serves as a foundational resource for researchers exploring neural pathways and their functionalities. Such datasets are increasingly essential for enhancing reproducibility studies and fostering future discovery within the field of neurobiology.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">As the work undergoes recognition in both academic circles and potential future citations, the absence of cited works at this point does not diminish its relevance. The ongoing elaboration of a robust collection of driver lines is anticipated to facilitate greater insights into nervous system functions and the underlying molecular mechanisms in Drosophila.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">In summary, this catalogue is expected to become a key reference point for neurobiologists and geneticists. Its impactful annotations of neuronal pathways and behavior in Drosophila are poised to drive further research initiatives, inspiring collaborative and innovative studies in neuronal science.</p>",
